{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/diversity-is-what-we-need-98b5f09287c1", "time": 1683014150.2128808, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/diversity-is-what-we-need-98b5f09287c1/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Diversity is what we need.. Thinking _now_ about the FUTURE of AI. | by Merzmensch | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Diversity is what we need.", "description": "Have you ever wondered about all the dogs? As Google Deep Dream was released, AI recognized \u2014 and amplified \u2014 in all pictures dog faces. Everywhere, in every corner: dogs, nothing but dogs\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://medium.com/merzazine/deep-dream-comes-true-eafb97df6cc5?source=friends_link&sk=6d50ebb59584b487183385009ba50f54", "anchor_text": "Google Deep Dream", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://www.fastcompany.com/3048941/why-googles-deep-dream-ai-hallucinates-in-dog-faces", "anchor_text": "FastCompany", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/pareidolia-of-ai-dba7cf44bfde?source=friends_link&sk=f22677820ca169764e2c076fea98ee6e", "anchor_text": "Pareidolia of AI", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://medium.com/merzazine/biggan-and-metamorphosis-of-everything-abc9463125ac?source=friends_link&sk=fde32a2f24a97d0a651c087709fb8a53", "anchor_text": "mix a dog with a space shuttle", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://colab.research.google.com/github/tensorflow/hub/blob/master/examples/colab/biggan_generation_with_tf_hub.ipynb", "anchor_text": "notebook", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://medium.com/merzazine/merzwoch-image-net-roulette-human-manipulation-and-beauty-of-nightmares-e435fed932b1?source=friends_link&sk=c80d4a07ad408f93cb1d8619813f2723", "anchor_text": "I was reporting about", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://medium.com/u/efbec1a070e4?source=post_page-----98b5f09287c1--------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Kate Crawford", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://medium.com/u/2f160965a3e7?source=post_page-----98b5f09287c1--------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Trevor Paglen", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://imagenet-roulette.paglen.com/", "anchor_text": "now offline", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://www.theverge.com/tldr/2019/9/16/20869538/imagenet-roulette-ai-classifier-web-tool-object-image-recognition", "anchor_text": "one-time labeling", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "http://www.fondazioneprada.org/project/training-humans/?lang=en", "anchor_text": "Training humans", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://news.artnet.com/art-world/imagenet-roulette-trevor-paglen-kate-crawford-1658305", "anchor_text": "had an impact on ImageNet", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://news.artnet.com/art-world/imagenet-roulette-trevor-paglen-kate-crawford-1658305", "anchor_text": "Source", "paragraph_index": 17}], "all_paragraphs": ["Have you ever wondered about all the dogs? As Google Deep Dream was released, AI recognized \u2014 and amplified \u2014 in all pictures dog faces. Everywhere, in every corner: dogs, nothing but dogs.", "The answer to this mysterium was simple \u2014 but alarming:", "In Deep Dream\u2019s case, that data set is from ImageNet, a database created by researchers at Stanford and Princeton who built a database of 14 million human-labeled images. But Google didn\u2019t use the whole database. Instead, they used a smaller subset of the ImageNet database released in 2012 for use in a contest\u2026 a subset which contained \u201cfine-grained classification of 120 dog sub-classes.\u201d(Source: FastCompany)", "Pareidolia of AI can only detect patterns and objects it\u2019s trained on. Datasets are what counts. The bigger they are, the better the quality.", "But there is another aspect: labeling.", "Do you remember, the mind-blowing times of BigGAN, as you could for the first time in the history mix a dog with a space shuttle?", "I found a strange phenomenon. If you want to generate a music instrument with BigGAN (notebook), you get a musician.", "The only explanation was: the person, who labeled images, hadn\u2019t done his job well. Instead of labeling just a music instrument, it labeled the whole image with a music instrument, including a performer. The right way would be to give a label \u201csaxophone\u201d to a picture with a saxophone, without any other elements or features.", "If you would ask an AI-driven robot, trained on this dataset, to bring you a saxophone, and it would bring you a saxophonist, you shouldn\u2019t blame the machine. It makes its work perfect. It\u2019s about us, who are erroneous.", "An inaccurate mislabeling can cause horrendous consequences, as we will see.", "Another experiment, I was reporting about, had shown the problems which evolve around insufficient labeling:", "Kate Crawford and Trevor Paglen demonstrated with their ImageNet-Roulette (now offline) the dangers of mislabeling.", "You could upload your image and \u2014 BANG! \u2014 you were described by the system. The description came from labels within ImageNet \u2014 and the labels were written by humans. Not accurate. With devastating consequences.", "In my case it was still more or less harmless (I uploaded an image of myself acting for a stage play \u201cKarol\u201d by S\u0142awomir Mro\u017cek):", "I was detected as a nonsmoker (\u201ca person who does not smoke tobacco\u201d). The huge rifle in my hands was overseen by AI.", "Though, there were other cases like labeling somebody like \u201crape suspect\u201d:", "The one-time labeling was exposed mislabeling within ImageNet. This project and connected Exhibition \u201cTraining humans\u201d by both artists had an impact on ImageNet:", "the researchers behind ImageNet announced that they would scrub more than half of the 1.2 million pictures in the dataset\u2019s \u201cpeople\u201d category. (Source)", "You have probably stumbled across such tweets within the last days:", "I was wondering, what\u2019s going on there. If you upload a bigger image to Twitter, it crops the preview in your timeline to the relevant parts of the image. If you open the whole image cropped here, you will see the following:", "People experimented with face images and discovered a phenomenon which could be described as a \u201cracism of Twitter\u201d, since people with white skin were prevailed and selected as \u201crelevant part\u201d, opposite to people of color.", "In juxtaposition Obama vs. Cat was Obama winner nevertheless:", "A wave of understandable alerts came across Twitter.", "But as we have seen \u2014 the issue is still in the labeling. I doubt Twitter was trained on racist intentions to hide Afroamericans and to be dominated by white faces. Or by men.", "The problem is most likely: the datasets. They were missing enough diversity. They were filled with white faces. They were biased. Human factor.", "We need more Diversity. Not as an alibi for \u201cbeing good\u201d to move things. Not as an \u201cOK, so here is some diversity if you are lucky with this\u201d.", "But DIVERSITY as an essential, indispensable, imperative, mandatory way of thinking.", "So, dear AI community, dear coders, dear labelers, dear AI researcher, everybody.", "This is not a drill. We are at the beginning of the feeding and training our AI systems. If we don\u2019t think in a perspective, if we ignore the future thinking, our AI will be biased.", "And in case AI will harm people, it\u2019s our, human fault.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Futurist. AI-driven Dadaist. Living in Germany, loving Japan, AI, mysteries, books, and stuff."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F98b5f09287c1&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F